A arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say that this shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
\"This body has a dual capacity.\"
\"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic\"
\"That's why it's very special, even though it's far from being a truly \"foreign\" way of life,\" commented Paul Davies C. W. of the University of State of Arizona, co-author of the report in the online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, are able to continue to develop after replacing the phosphorus with the arsenic.
“We are wondering what is still possible,” said Ariel Anbar D. from Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the area of research of life beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the find, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of an alien life.
That was not the case.
The discovery - indicates that, in other global environments, organizations could be able to use other elements to act on biochemistry and that the \"standard\" set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed - commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Planetary and Spacial Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
\"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure,\" Cockell added.
It wasn't a random discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake as it has high levels of arsenic.
arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
\"The arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behaviour is really similar to that of phosphorus\"
As a result, organizations have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately.
\"But the arsenic is different enough so it doesn't work exactly like the phosphor; it penetrates inside and somehow gums the work of our biochemical machine,\" Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing levels of arsenic that it was able to adapt to and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more frequent.
Jamie S. Foster, Assistant Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
The arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the existence of the Earth, she said, so the researchers assumed that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways to form life, not just how life on Earth was formed at first, said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
