The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
Persons must go to the Service Centres for Visa Applicants prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa processing procedure at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicants Service Centres (ASC, according to its English-language acronyms) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the applicants, including the following:
The total cost for processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another payment for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas on demand (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for commercial and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visas will not have to interview with the Consular Representative, they will only be present at the nearest CSA where they will present the documents, and their fingerprints will be taken.
Because of the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants wishing to have a second meeting to be interviewed in the Consular Section will be less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101101_Visas-FAQs.html.
