The discovery will be presented at a press conference tomorrow Thursday, 13:00 a.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington for astrobiology experts, science that studies the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the Universe.
When she cited the press, NASA assured that it would present an impact on the search for extraterrestrial life - which caused speculation by experts from other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that there are creatures similar to us and in hostile environments that were thought to be uninhabited and would put on the table the possibility of becoming intelligent beings like humans if their living conditions were improved.
It seems that we are talking about a microbe discovered at the bottom of the Mono Lake in the Yosemite National Park, California, which lives in an environment that we thought was too poisonous for any form of life, because the lake is rich in arsenic.
In any case, the creature uses arsenic as a way of life and this ability makes us think that a similar life could exist on other planets that do not have our voluntary atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it proves that there is another form of life, a second form of life, different from that we know.
The space agency will communicate the true scope of the discoveries at tomorrow's press conference on Thursday.
At the conference will participate in the geobiology Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who study Titan (the largest satellite in Saturn), from the perspective that his chemistry is similar to that of the Earth.
