A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
The United Nations proposed to Cancún yesterday a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas reduction (GES) that corresponds almost a third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan lies in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding commitments by industrialized countries to reduce.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolise from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact ampoules or, better, by light-diade ampoules (DEL or LED), most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to light humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the global car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen, last year, major issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, whose Canada has engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should move the overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will need to take this balance sheet off again to stabilize the 2-degree increase in climate by 2020 in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, 5%, produced from light.
With fluocompact ampoules, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact ampoules last on average from 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company has also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have posted reserves for fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and have to be disposed of as hazardous wastes, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the manufacturers put in place the instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluocompact bulb, but rather coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost 2.5 billion.
