Revenge hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of hypocrisy which governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by the regression.
But proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The \"extraordinary\" revelations on Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi owns), and the sinisterly caricature profile of Khadafi has long been for sketch-based cabaret artists.
The rule that secret records should only be composed of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Temples or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts doesn't like to do unpublished research (he doesn't know where to look for news about the inexistant), but because those who want to be occult believe only what they already know, and who reconfirm what they've already learned.
That's Dan Brown's mechanism of success.
Same for secret files.
The informer is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (if not it could be, as I know, editor in Libération), who hold only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
Then why did the revelations on these files make such a noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of states can telephone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small exercises of representation, have become spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place US diplomacy under bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world has a significant impact on the prestige of the state department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims and the \"hard people\" in a crisis.
But let us come to the profound nature of what has happened.
At Orwell's time, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had completely proven itself since, being able to control each movement through the telephone, every transaction, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the power's eye.
But when we show, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as a citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret will never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, because it is within the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks did no wrong to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on-line any information reserved - this would be to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope that we can maintain confidential relationships by telephone.
Nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the time being, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents who discreetly move in diligence to uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at the very least, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in key closed drawers: at the bottom, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving forward in crabs, that is to say backward.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a telegraph on wires (telephones).
The videocassettes (analog) had enabled film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (numerics) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macro-portions.
With the high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communications policy and technology will return to horse-ridden cars.
One last comment.
Once, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
Now, it is the embassies who ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France bids its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review compliance with the rapidly released financing promises (such as fast start or early funding) made by developed countries.
