Transparency is appreciated and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
In 2010, the EU announced EUR 2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track to meet its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, “new and additional” in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without prejudice to the Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what \"new and additional\" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose procedure has been blocked by France.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission considered the reference year 2009: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France believes that the financing of ‘all new projects’ in 2010 is “new and additional”
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or at the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even diminish), it claims to respect its commitment to new and additional funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution between gifts and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent to a euro that is given...In addition, it should be counted for its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has only to make such a reasoning: it - it respects - its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for itself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, France only places 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice step-by-step tour!
In short, in its fast start funding, France has a double swindle: on the one hand, on the other, the evolution of action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, she can make it believe that it spends EUR 420 million - new and additional - in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems to be true that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries were not completely dubious...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, short-term issue, compared with all climate discussions.
But it could be an extra sand grain in the immense machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully that will not be the case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn lessons from this first year of early funding.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): the issue of ‘additionality’ or the method of accounting for loans will not escape.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
